[3] UK (1st fatality)
Date: Fri 19 Apr 2013
Source: The Daily Telegraph [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/10006706/Measles-epidemic-claims-1st-death.html


The measles epidemic appears to have claimed its 1st victim after health officials confirmed that a young man who died was suffering from the disease. The death follows repeated warnings that the rising numbers of children and adults infected meant fatalities were likely. More than 800 cases of measles have now been confirmed in Wales, with experts predicting that number will double within weeks, and concerns that it could spread across the UK. Doctors have warned that up to 2 million children in England and Wales are at risk of contracting measles, because their parents refused to allow them to have vaccinations during the MMR scare.

The man, aged 25 of Port Tennant, Swansea, died on Thursday [18 Apr 2013] morning. Neighbours said he had been suffering from measles since last week, and they believed the new father may have contracted the disease from his baby daughter. They said he also had other health problems including asthma, which combined with measles could have led to his death. Tests on Friday [19 Apr 2013] confirmed that the victim was suffering from measles when he died, but the cause of death has yet to be established. Dr Marion Lyons, Director of Health Protection said: "Whatever the cause of death in this case, we should not be surprised if, as the outbreak grows, we start to see deaths."

Experts are now calling for a national "catch-up" campaign to prevent the disease spreading throughout the UK. There are particular concerns that the capital [London] is vulnerable. A decade ago, nearly half of young children in London did not receive vaccinations because of fears about a link made in research between MMR and autism, which was later discredited.

Health officials say that in developed countries, around one in every 1000 people who contracts measles will die, with yet more likely to suffer complications such as deafness and blindness. The last death from measles in the UK was in 2008, and before that, the last case of the disease killing an otherwise healthy person was in 1992, long before the MMR scare.

Latest figures revealed there are 808 confirmed cases of the disease in the outbreak in south Wales, including 77 patients being treated in hospital. Extra clinics are expected to be held at hospitals around Swansea this weekend with health officials anticipating a rush of parents and children wanting the jab. Health workers have also visited local schools to immunise hundreds of children.

[Byline: Laura Donnelly]

