[5] UK (Wiltshire)
Date: Tue 16 Apr 2013
Source: Wiltshire Times [edited]
http://www.wiltshiretimes.co.uk/news/latestheadlines/10358331.Case_of_measles_confirmed_at_Devizes_School/


A case of measles has been confirmed at Devizes School, prompting the headteacher to urge parents to make sure their children are inoculated with the MMR vaccine. He said: "We have posted a letter on our website and are sending hard copies of this home with pupils, urging parents to make sure their children are protected from this potentially dangerous disease. The letter being sent home is from Maggie Rae, Wiltshire's director of public health. It reads: "Whilst the associated risk from this particular case is low, we wanted to take this opportunity to raise awareness of the importance of protecting children against measles, mumps and rubella (MMR)."

"An outbreak of measles such as in South Wales occurs when the number of people in a population who are not vaccinated against measles gets too high. "In Wiltshire, we have good uptake of the MMR vaccine. The MMR vaccination is the safest and most effective way to protect both the individual and those who cannot receive vaccination for any reason, for example because they are too young to have the vaccine or have a health condition which prevents receiving vaccinations.

