[7] Nigeria
Date: Thu 18 Apr 2013
Source: Leadership [edited]
http://leadership.ng/nga/articles/52286/2013/04/18/measles_outbreak_senate_blames_suspicion_vaccine_rejection.html


Debating an ongoing measles outbreak which has killed 36 children and hospitalised about 3588 in northern Nigeria, according to Senate figures, federal lawmakers say widespread suspicion and deliberate misinformation on the vaccine has aggravated the spread of the epidemic.

Also, Senators passed for 2nd reading a Bill for an Act to repeal the "archaic" 1926 Quarantine Act and enact the Nigeria Public Health (Quarantine Isolation and Emergency Health Matters Procedure) to prevent the introduction, spread of, and regulate steps for the containment of dangerous infectious and communicable diseases, organisms and agents in Nigeria. The Quarantine Bill was referred to the Senate committees on health and agriculture for further legislative work. The report is expected in 2 weeks.

Senate President David Mark accused certain interests of distorting facts about the vaccines for measles, polio and other preventable diseases for "political reasons." Coming on the heels of the recent killing of 10 polio vaccinators in Kano state, a proposal to provide security backup for vaccinators failed as Senators rejected the move at plenary. Mark's disclosure was a sequel to a motion for an "urgent sensitization and awareness campaign, and a supply of vaccines to measles affected areas," sponsored by Sen. Danladi Sankara (Jigawa, PDP) and 28 others.

Mark [stated]: "There is no doubt that people go about deliberately misinforming the ignorant in the society about the consequences of routine immunisation or vaccination. Well, some use it for political reasons. If you look at the states that are affected currently, it is more prevalent in the northern states, and I think that all of us from the northern states must have the courage to go back to our constituencies and educate our people that this (vaccination) is the right thing for them to do."

[Byline: Edegbe Odemwingie and Jonathan Nda-isaiah]

